Data Scientists From Non-Computer Science Background

Muhsina Elampilakkattil

20 November 2018

  • Introduction
    • About the Dataset
    • Types of Data Scientists

Introduction

Data Scientist is Programming skills and statistical knowledge are the most essential skills of a data scientist.

Can anyone from a non-computer science background be a data scientist? How can I be data scientist with a non-computer science background? The most common questions from some aspiring data scientists. In fact, these were the same questions which I googled 7 months back. Data Scientist is the sexiest job of the 21st century. There are so many people from diverse backgrounds trying to get this hottest job. Some of them think this job is meant for people from the computer science background. When I started thinking about a career in data science, I had lots of questions flying over my head. What programming language do I have to learn? Which online source will help me learning to programme? From where I get public datasets to do projects? etc.. I thought it would be better if I get answers for these questions from people who are currently working as data scientists and from the non-computer science background. In this exploratory analysis, I will be trying to get answers for these questions from data scientists with non-computer science background.

About the Dataset

Kaggle conducted a worldwide survey to know about the state of data science and machine learning. The survey was live for one week in October. The datasets include 23,859 responses and 395 variables. These variables are the answers to survey questions.

When survey respondents selected the Other category, an option was given for a text response. These text responses were separated and shuffled to protect user privacy.

We need to load multiple libraries and datasets to start the analysis.

Types of Data Scientists

Data science combines several disciplines, including statistics, data analysis, machine learning, and computer science. Four types of data science jobs are, ** The Data Analyst ** The Data Engineer ** The Machine Learning Engineer ** The Data Science Generalist

Therefore, here we are grouping Data Scientists, Data Analysts, and Data Engineers together. We are considering undergraduate major (Question 4) as the attribute to subset the data as respondents working as data scientists with a non-computer science major. We need to filter out responses with an option I am a student to the Question 7 (In what industry is your current employer/contract?) to ensure the respondent is a working as a data scientist.

#Data Scientists
survey%>%
filter(Q6 %in% c("Data Scientist", "Data Engineer", "Data Analyst"),
      !is.na(Q8),
       !is.na(Q5),
      Q7 != "I am a student") %>%  
  mutate(CS= ifelse(Q5=="Computer science (software engineering, etc.)", TRUE, FALSE)) %>%
  select(Q6, CS)   %>%
  group_by(Q6, CS)  %>%
summarize(n= n()) %>%
mutate(pct = n/ sum(n) * 100 ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x= reorder(Q6, n), y = n, fill= CS)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("dodgerblue4", "gray70")) +
  labs(title= "Data Scientists", x="", y="Count") +
        annotate("text", x = "Data Analyst", y = 1665, label = "73.8%", hjust= 2) +
        annotate("text", x = "Data Engineer", y = 667, label = "47.4%", hjust= 1.2) +
        annotate("text", x = "Data Scientist", y = 3739, label = "67.7%", hjust= 2) +
  coord_flip() + 
  theme_minimal(base_size= 10)

# Core wrapping function
wrap.it <- function(x, len)
{ 
  sapply(x, function(y) paste(strwrap(y, len), 
                              collapse = "\n"), 
         USE.NAMES = FALSE)
}


# Call this function with a list or vector
wrap.labels <- function(x, len)
{
  if (is.list(x))
  {
    lapply(x, wrap.it, len)
  } else {
    wrap.it(x, len)
  }
}


label <- wrap.labels(activities$Activities, 30)

activities%>%
mutate(pct = count/ sum(count) * 100 ) %>%
arrange(desc(count)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x= reorder(Activities, desc(count)), y= count)) +
  geom_bar(stat= "identity", fill= "blue") +
  geom_text(aes(label= paste0(round(pct,2),"%", sep="")),
      position= position_dodge(0), color= "black", size= 3)+
  labs(title= "Activities important in the current role (NonCS)", x= "", y= "Count") +
    scale_x_discrete(labels= wrap.labels(activities$Activities, 30))+
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal(base_size= 8)
